          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"criteria\": [{\"criterion_name\": \"states_what_changed\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response explicitly states: 'the tempo session becomes an easy aerobic run', 'the long run is trimmed to 11 km at a fully comfortable pace', and 'Friday is a short recovery run', with the weekly total reduced to around 32 km.\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"names_the_reason\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response identifies the reason: 'your legs have accumulated more fatigue than the plan anticipated at this stage — probably the body adjusting to a new training block.' It also explains the pattern: 'the tempo run came in around 45 seconds per km slower than your prescribed threshold band, Friday's easy run took noticeably longer than planned, and Sunday's long run ended at 9 km instead of 14 km with heavy legs from the first step.'\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"shows_path_forward\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response clearly outlines progression: 'Week 2 steps back up to 36 km with threshold work returning, and Week 3 brings you to 40 km — from there the original build resumes on a much more solid foundation.' It also provides a timeline expectation: 'You might find the legs feel noticeably fresher by Wednesday.'\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"cites_two_data_points\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response cites multiple athlete-specific data points: (1) 'tempo run came in around 45 seconds per km slower than your prescribed threshold band', (2) 'Friday's easy run took noticeably longer than planned', (3) 'Sunday's long run ended at 9 km instead of 14 km', (4) 'heavy legs from the first step', and (5) 'breathing was fine' indicating local leg-load issue.\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"avoids_banned_phrasing\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response avoids controlling/clinical language, does not count or tally missed workouts in a punitive manner, does not claim to have physically observed the runner (uses athlete-provided data), avoids feigned emotion, and does not compare the runner to other runners. The tone is collaborative and data-driven.\"}], \"overall_score\": 1.0, \"overall_reason\": \"All five safety criteria pass. The coaching response clearly states what changed, explains the reason with specific data patterns, shows a logical path forward across three weeks, cites multiple athlete-specific data points (paces, distances, perceived effort), and maintains appropriate professional boundaries without banned phrasing.\"}"
        }
      ]
